ElementDescription: The NDAR Global Unique Identifier (GUID) for research subject
Subject ID how it's defined in lab/project
Date on which the interview/genetic test/sampling/imaging/biospecimen was completed. MM/DD/YYYY
Age in months at the time of the interview/test/sampling/imaging.
Notes: Age is rounded to chronological month. If the research participant is 15-days-old at time of interview, the appropriate value would be 0 months. If the participant is 16-days-old, the value would be 1 month.

ElementDescription: Sex of subject at birth
Notes: M = Male; F = Female; O=Other; NR = Not reported

ElementDescription: If you were trying to improve mental health services in your clinic, how confident do you feel that you know what are the main issues to focus on?
Notes: 0= Not at all confident; 1=A little confident; 2=Somewhat confident; 3= Very confident; 99=missing

ElementDescription: If you were trying to improve mental health services in your clinic, how confident do you feel that you know what area(s) to focus on first?
Notes: 0= Not at all confident; 1=A little confident; 2=Somewhat confident; 3= Very confident; 99=missing

ElementDescription: How confident are you in coming up with solutions to problems in mental healthcare at your health facility?
Notes: 0= Not at all confident; 1=A little confident; 2=Somewhat confident; 3= Very confident; 99=missing

ElementDescription: How confident are you in implementing solutions to problems in mental healthcare at your health facility?
Notes: 0= Not at all confident; 1=A little confident; 2=Somewhat confident; 3= Very confident; 99=missing

ElementDescription: How confident are you in tracking and/or measuring whether solutions have worked to solve problems in mental healthcare at your health facility?
Notes: 0= Not at all confident; 1=A little confident; 2=Somewhat confident; 3= Very confident; 99=missing

ElementDescription: Leadership at this health facility thinks my work on mental healthcare is important.
Leadership at this health facility is supportive of me trying new things to improve mental healthcare.
I understand the barriers patients face in accessing mental healthcare at this health facility, staying engaged in mental healthcare and ultimately recovering from their symtpoms.
I feel like I am working alone with little support.
I feel I am part of a team working together for a common goal.
I only do this work to earn money but I would not say I enjoy it.
I am willing to put in extra effort to ensure patients get the best quality mental healthcare.
I am so overwhelmed with my work that it is hard to take anything else on.
No one seems to care about the quality of my work.
I have all of the skills that I need in order to adequately treat the patients I see in our clinic.
